This conceptual diagram visualizes the holistic pipeline from sensor input data (Input Data Types) to successful real-world deployments (Downstream Tasks).

It maps how the inherent data quality and type provided by various Sensor Modalities directly define the input of the system.

These sensors—including RGB-D, Thermal, and LiDAR—provide the fundamental data that drives all subsequent computational analysis.

Crucial Processing & Algorithms (like Demosaicing, Segmentation, and Mosaicing) serve as the intermediate engine, extracting meaningful features and information from the raw data.

This analysis is grounded in established Literature Integration, drawing on pioneering works such as Lowe's SIFT (Features), Ronneberger's U-Net (Segmentation), and He's ResNet (Deep Learning).

The extracted information must satisfy strict hardware and operation constraints, mapped in the third pillar as System Characteristics (e.g., Latency, Power, Robustness).

A continuous feedback loop dictates how algorithms influence these performance metrics while, in reverse, hardware sets hard operational boundaries.

Ultimately, these upstream constraints (data type, processing speed, and environment) are what are enabled or limited by to determine the feasibility of high-level tasks.

This dictates the success of diverse Vision-Based Applications, ranging from high-stakes Medical Diagnosis and Autonomous Navigation to efficient Industrial Inspection.

The concept map effectively provides a structured decision framework, linking technical capabilities to strategic application selection through a cause-and-effect relationship.
